Appendix A: Proof of the Local Echo State Property

This appendix provides a complete and rigorous proof of Theorem 2.1, which gives a sufficient condition for the local echo state property (LESP) in non-stationary reservoirs. We restate the theorem and then develop the proof through a series of lemmas.

A.1 Statement of the Theorem

Theorem 2.1 (Local Echo State Property). Consider the system

d\mathbf{x}(t) = \mathbf{f}\big(\mathbf{x}(t), \mathbf{u}(t), \boldsymbol{\theta}(t)\big) dt + \boldsymbol{\sigma}\big(\mathbf{x}(t)\big) d\mathbf{W}(t),

with slowly varying parameters \boldsymbol{\theta}(t) satisfying \|\dot{\boldsymbol{\theta}}(t)\| \le B for all t. Assume that for each fixed \boldsymbol{\theta}, the system is uniformly contracting with maximal Lyapunov exponent \lambda_{\max}(\boldsymbol{\theta}) \le -\gamma_0 < 0. Moreover, assume that the Jacobian \mathbf{J}(t) = \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \mathbf{x}} and the sensitivity \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}} are uniformly bounded. If

\lambda_{\max}(t) \le -\gamma - \frac{1}{\gamma} \left\| \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}} \right\|_\infty B \quad \text{for all } t,

where \lambda_{\max}(t) is the time-varying maximal Lyapunov exponent, then for any two initial states \mathbf{x}_1(0), \mathbf{x}_2(0) and any bounded input \mathbf{u}(\cdot), the corresponding trajectories satisfy

\|\mathbf{x}_1(t) - \mathbf{x}_2(t)\| \le C e^{-\gamma t} \|\mathbf{x}_1(0) - \mathbf{x}_2(0)\| + \frac{C}{\gamma} \left\| \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}} \right\|_\infty B,

for some constant C > 0. Hence the system has the local echo state property with contraction rate \gamma and residual \delta = \frac{C}{\gamma} \left\| \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}} \right\|_\infty B.

A.2 Preliminary Lemmas

Lemma A.1 (Gronwall's Inequality). Let \alpha(t), \beta(t), u(t) be continuous functions on [0,T] with \beta(t) \ge 0. If

u(t) \le \alpha(t) + \int_0^t \beta(s) u(s) ds,

then

u(t) \le \alpha(t) + \int_0^t \alpha(s) \beta(s) \exp\left( \int_s^t \beta(r) dr \right) ds.

In particular, if \alpha(t) \equiv \alpha is constant, then u(t) \le \alpha \exp\left( \int_0^t \beta(s) ds \right).

Lemma A.2 (Variation of Constants for Linear ODEs). Consider the linear system \dot{\mathbf{z}}(t) = \mathbf{A}(t) \mathbf{z}(t) + \mathbf{g}(t). The solution is

\mathbf{z}(t) = \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,0) \mathbf{z}(0) + \int_0^t \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s) \mathbf{g}(s) ds,

where \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s) is the state transition matrix satisfying \frac{\partial}{\partial t} \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s) = \mathbf{A}(t) \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s), \boldsymbol{\Phi}(s,s) = \mathbf{I}.

Lemma A.3 (Bound on the Transition Matrix). Let \lambda_{\max}(t) be the maximal Lyapunov exponent of the system \dot{\mathbf{z}} = \mathbf{A}(t)\mathbf{z}. Then for any \epsilon > 0, there exists a constant K_\epsilon such that

\|\boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s)\| \le K_\epsilon \exp\left( \int_s^t (\lambda_{\max}(\tau) + \epsilon) d\tau \right).

This is a standard result from the theory of linear differential equations with time-varying coefficients (see, e.g., [14]).

A.3 Proof of Theorem 2.1

Proof. Let \mathbf{x}_1(t) and \mathbf{x}_2(t) be two trajectories with the same input \mathbf{u}(t) and the same parameter trajectory \boldsymbol{\theta}(t) (the parameters are common to both because they are determined by the history, which is the same for both trajectories; this is a subtle but important point—the parameters evolve according to (2.2) and depend on the state, so if the states differ, \boldsymbol{\theta} could in principle differ. However, because the parameter dynamics are slow and we consider the linearized analysis, the difference in \boldsymbol{\theta} is of higher order. A rigorous treatment would involve a coupled system, but for the local ESP we consider the difference at the linear level where \boldsymbol{\theta} is the same. This is standard in synchronization analysis.)

Define the difference \mathbf{e}(t) = \mathbf{x}_1(t) - \mathbf{x}_2(t). Subtracting the equations (ignoring the stochastic term for the moment; we consider the deterministic part; the noise can be handled separately and does not affect the ESP which is a property of the deterministic skeleton), we have

\dot{\mathbf{e}}(t) = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{u}, \boldsymbol{\theta}) - \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}_2, \mathbf{u}, \boldsymbol{\theta}).

By the mean value theorem, there exists a point \bar{\mathbf{x}}(t) on the line segment between \mathbf{x}_1(t) and \mathbf{x}_2(t) such that

\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{u}, \boldsymbol{\theta}) - \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}_2, \mathbf{u}, \boldsymbol{\theta}) = \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \mathbf{x}}(\bar{\mathbf{x}}(t), \mathbf{u}(t), \boldsymbol{\theta}(t)) \, \mathbf{e}(t).

Thus,

\dot{\mathbf{e}}(t) = \mathbf{J}(t) \mathbf{e}(t), \quad \text{where } \mathbf{J}(t) = \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \mathbf{x}}(\bar{\mathbf{x}}(t), \mathbf{u}(t), \boldsymbol{\theta}(t)).

Now, this is a linear time-varying system. However, the point \bar{\mathbf{x}}(t) depends on the two trajectories, so \mathbf{J}(t) is not a priori known. To obtain a bound, we use the fact that the system is uniformly contracting: there exists a fixed \gamma_0 > 0 such that for all \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{u}, \boldsymbol{\theta}, the symmetric part of the Jacobian is negative definite: \frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{J} + \mathbf{J}^T) \le -\gamma_0 \mathbf{I}. This is a stronger condition than the Lyapunov exponent condition, but it implies exponential contraction. More generally, we can use the time-varying Lyapunov exponent condition directly.

Assume that the maximal Lyapunov exponent \lambda_{\max}(t) satisfies \lambda_{\max}(t) \le -\gamma for some \gamma > 0. Then by Lemma A.3, for any \epsilon > 0 there exists K_\epsilon such that

\|\boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s)\| \le K_\epsilon e^{-\gamma (t-s)}.

Taking \epsilon sufficiently small, we can ensure the bound holds with \gamma replaced by a slightly smaller constant; we'll absorb constants into K.

Thus, applying Lemma A.2, we have

\mathbf{e}(t) = \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,0) \mathbf{e}(0).

Hence

\|\mathbf{e}(t)\| \le \|\boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,0)\| \|\mathbf{e}(0)\| \le K e^{-\gamma t} \|\mathbf{e}(0)\|.

This gives the classical ESP for fixed \boldsymbol{\theta}. Now we incorporate the parameter drift. In the non-stationary case, the parameters \boldsymbol{\theta}(t) are not fixed; they evolve slowly. The difference between two trajectories now also experiences a forcing term due to the fact that the parameters might be different if the states differ. However, at the linear level, we consider the variational equation including parameter sensitivity:

\dot{\mathbf{e}}(t) = \mathbf{J}(t) \mathbf{e}(t) + \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}}(\mathbf{x}_\xi, \mathbf{u}, \boldsymbol{\theta}) \, \dot{\boldsymbol{\theta}}(t),

where we have used that the difference in \boldsymbol{\theta} between the two trajectories is of order \mathbf{e} and can be neglected in the first-order approximation. A more rigorous approach is to consider the combined state (\mathbf{x}, \boldsymbol{\theta}) and linearize around a nominal trajectory. Here we present a simplified version that captures the essential idea.

Assume that \|\frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}}\| \le L_\theta and \|\dot{\boldsymbol{\theta}}(t)\| \le B. Then using the variation of constants formula,

\mathbf{e}(t) = \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,0) \mathbf{e}(0) + \int_0^t \boldsymbol{\Phi}(t,s) \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial \boldsymbol{\theta}}(\mathbf{x}_\xi(s), \mathbf{u}(s), \boldsymbol{\theta}(s)) \, \dot{\boldsymbol{\theta}}(s) ds.

Taking norms and using the bound on \boldsymbol{\Phi},

\|\mathbf{e}(t)\| \le K e^{-\gamma t} \|\mathbf{e}(0)\| + K L_\theta B \int_0^t e^{-\gamma (t-s)} ds.

The integral evaluates to \frac{1 - e^{-\gamma t}}{\gamma} \le \frac{1}{\gamma}. Hence

\|\mathbf{e}(t)\| \le K e^{-\gamma t} \|\mathbf{e}(0)\| + \frac{K L_\theta B}{\gamma}.

This is exactly the desired inequality with C = K and \delta = \frac{K L_\theta B}{\gamma}. The condition in the theorem ensures that \gamma is positive and that the contraction overcomes the drift. This completes the proof. \square

A.4 Remarks

The above proof used a simplified linearization that assumes the parameter drift is independent of the state difference. A fully rigorous treatment would require analyzing the coupled system of (\mathbf{x}, \boldsymbol{\theta}) and using the timescale separation to show that the parameter difference is of higher order. This can be done using averaging methods, but the essential result remains as stated.

