Appendix B: Stochastic Calculus for Neural Dynamics

This appendix provides background on stochastic differential equations (SDEs) used in modeling neural activity. We focus on the Stratonovich interpretation and its properties.

B.1 Itô and Stratonovich Integrals

An SDE can be written in two equivalent forms. The Itô form:

d\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},t) dt + \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{x},t) d\mathbf{W},

and the Stratonovich form:

d\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},t) dt + \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{x},t) \circ d\mathbf{W}.

The notation \circ denotes the Stratonovich integral, which follows the ordinary rules of calculus. For example, if \mathbf{G} is independent of \mathbf{x}, both forms coincide. The conversion between them involves a correction term:

\mathbf{f}_{\text{Itô}} = \mathbf{f}_{\text{Strat}} - \frac{1}{2} \sum_j \frac{\partial \mathbf{G}}{\partial x_j} \mathbf{G}_j,

where \mathbf{G}_j is the j-th column of \mathbf{G}.

In neural modeling, the noise arises from channel fluctuations and synaptic release, which have finite correlation time; thus the Stratonovich interpretation is physically more appropriate. We adopt Stratonovich throughout.

B.2 The Chain Rule (Stratonovich)

For a function \phi(\mathbf{x},t), the Stratonovich differential is

d\phi = \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial t} dt + \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial \mathbf{x}} \circ d\mathbf{x} = \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial t} dt + \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial \mathbf{x}} \mathbf{f} dt + \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial \mathbf{x}} \mathbf{G} \circ d\mathbf{W}.

This follows the ordinary chain rule, which is why Stratonovich is convenient for physical applications.

B.3 Fokker-Planck Equation

The probability density p(\mathbf{x},t) of the solution of an SDE satisfies the Fokker-Planck equation. For the Stratonovich SDE

d\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},t) dt + \mathbf{G}(\mathbf{x},t) \circ d\mathbf{W},

the corresponding Fokker-Planck equation in Itô form is

\frac{\partial p}{\partial t} = -\nabla \cdot (\mathbf{f} p) + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i,j} \frac{\partial^2}{\partial x_i \partial x_j} \left( [\mathbf{G}\mathbf{G}^T]_{ij} p \right),

where the drift \mathbf{f} here is the Itô drift. If the original is Stratonovich, we must convert the drift accordingly. Alternatively, one can work directly with the Stratonovich representation and use the corresponding Fokker-Planck equation with a modified drift. In practice, for neural models, we often use the Itô form for numerical simulation, but the Stratonovich interpretation is used for analytical derivations to preserve the chain rule.

B.4 Application to Neural Models

Consider a network of Izhikevich neurons. The deterministic part is given by ODEs. Adding noise in the voltage equation (e.g., channel noise) leads to an SDE. Typically, the noise is additive (independent of voltage), in which case Itô and Stratonovich coincide. However, if the noise is multiplicative (e.g., conductance-based noise), then the interpretation matters. In such cases, we adopt Stratonovich to maintain the correct physical behavior.

