Appendix C: Information Theory for Point Processes

This appendix derives the expression for mutual information between a stimulus and a spike train, and the Kullback-Leibler divergence for point processes.

C.1 Spike Trains as Point Processes

A spike train can be represented as a set of event times \{t_i\} on an interval [0,T]. The conditional intensity function \lambda(t|\mathcal{H}_t) gives the instantaneous firing probability given the history \mathcal{H}_t. For an inhomogeneous Poisson process, \lambda(t) is deterministic given the history (which may include past spikes).

C.2 Likelihood of a Point Process

The likelihood of observing a spike train with event times t_1,\dots,t_n on [0,T] under a conditional intensity \lambda(t) is

L = \left( \prod_{i=1}^n \lambda(t_i) \right) \exp\left( -\int_0^T \lambda(s) ds \right).

In discrete time with small bins \Delta t, this becomes a product of Bernoulli probabilities.

C.3 Mutual Information

For a point process with conditional intensity depending on a stimulus S, the mutual information between the spike train and the stimulus is

I(S; \text{spikes}) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \log \frac{p(\text{spikes}|S)}{p(\text{spikes})} \right].

Using the chain rule for point processes, this can be expressed as an integral over time:

I(S; \text{spikes}) = \int_0^T \mathbb{E}\left[ \lambda(t|S) \log \frac{\lambda(t|S)}{\nu(t)} - (\lambda(t|S) - \nu(t)) \right] dt,

where \nu(t) = \mathbb{E}[\lambda(t|S)] is the marginal intensity. The expectation is over stimulus and spike train realizations. This formula is derived from the likelihood and the fact that for a Poisson process, the log-likelihood ratio has a simple form.

Derivation sketch: For a small time interval [t,t+dt), the probability of a spike is approximately \lambda(t|S) dt. The contribution to the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the conditional and marginal distributions over this interval is \lambda(t|S) dt \log \frac{\lambda(t|S)}{\nu(t)} + (1-\lambda(t|S) dt) \log \frac{1-\lambda(t|S) dt}{1-\nu(t) dt}. Expanding the logarithm and keeping terms of order dt yields the expression above after taking expectations and integrating.

C.4 Kullback-Leibler Divergence for Point Processes

For two point processes with intensities \lambda_1(t) and \lambda_2(t) on [0,T], the KL divergence is

D_{KL}(\lambda_1 \| \lambda_2) = \int_0^T \left( \lambda_1(t) \log \frac{\lambda_1(t)}{\lambda_2(t)} - (\lambda_1(t) - \lambda_2(t)) \right) dt.

This is a standard result and is used in the information bottleneck derivation.

