Appendix D: Derivation of the Three-Factor Plasticity Rule

This appendix provides a detailed derivation of the three-factor learning rule (3.2) using the likelihood ratio method.

D.1 Setup

Consider a single postsynaptic neuron with Poisson firing rate \lambda(t) = \exp(\mathbf{w}^T \mathbf{x}(t)), where \mathbf{x}(t) is a vector of presynaptic inputs (including eligibility traces). The probability of a spike in a small interval [t,t+dt) is \lambda(t) dt. Over a time interval [0,T], the likelihood of observing a spike train with event times \{t_i\} is

p(\{t_i\} | \mathbf{w}) = \prod_i \lambda(t_i) \exp\left( -\int_0^T \lambda(s) ds \right).

We have a task variable Z (e.g., a class label) that we want to predict. The mutual information between the spike train and Z is I(\text{spikes}; Z). We aim to maximize an objective that trades off information about Z against information in the spikes and metabolic cost:

\mathcal{L} = I(\text{spikes}; Z) - \beta I(\text{spikes}; \text{input}) - \gamma \mathbb{E}[\text{spike count}].

However, direct optimization is difficult. We use variational bounds.

D.2 Variational Bound on I(\text{spikes}; Z)

We have

I(\text{spikes}; Z) = H(Z) - H(Z|\text{spikes}) = H(Z) + \mathbb{E}[\log p(Z|\text{spikes})].

For any variational distribution q(Z|\text{spikes}),

\mathbb{E}[\log p(Z|\text{spikes})] \ge \mathbb{E}[\log q(Z|\text{spikes})] - D_{KL}(p(\cdot|\text{spikes}) \| q(\cdot|\text{spikes})).

Thus, a lower bound is \mathbb{E}[\log q(Z|\text{spikes})] - \text{const}. We will use q as a parametric model (e.g., linear readout) that we can optimize.

Similarly, we can bound I(\text{spikes}; \text{input}) from above using a variational marginal r(\text{spikes}):

I(\text{spikes}; \text{input}) \le \mathbb{E}\left[ \log \frac{p(\text{spikes}|\text{input})}{r(\text{spikes})} \right].

Choosing r as a Poisson process with constant rate is a common choice.

D.3 Objective for a Single Time Step

For online learning, we consider each time step independently (with appropriate temporal smoothing via eligibility traces). At time t, let y_t \in \{0,1\} be the spike indicator. The log-likelihood for that bin (assuming small \Delta t) is

\log p(y_t | \mathbf{x}_t, \mathbf{w}) = y_t \log(\lambda_t \Delta t) - \lambda_t \Delta t - \log(y_t!) \approx y_t \log(\lambda_t \Delta t) - \lambda_t \Delta t,

ignoring constants. The term \log(\lambda_t \Delta t) can be split as \log \lambda_t + \log \Delta t; the constant \log \Delta t does not affect gradients.

The contribution to the lower bound on I(\text{spikes}; Z) is y_t \log q(z_t|y_t), where q(z_t|y_t) is the variational distribution (which may depend on the entire history, but we approximate it as depending only on the current spike). Similarly, the upper bound on I(\text{spikes}; \text{input}) involves \log p(y_t|\mathbf{x}_t) - \log r(y_t), where r(y_t) is a baseline (e.g., the marginal probability of a spike). The metabolic cost is \gamma y_t.

Thus, an instantaneous objective (to be maximized) is

J_t = \log p(y_t|\mathbf{x}_t) - \log r(y_t) + \beta \log q(z_t|y_t) - \gamma y_t.

We want to maximize the expected value of J_t over time.

D.4 Gradient with Respect to Weights

To compute the gradient of \mathbb{E}[J_t] with respect to \mathbf{w}, we use the likelihood ratio (REINFORCE) trick because y_t is a random variable whose distribution depends on \mathbf{w}. We have

\nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \mathbb{E}[J_t] = \mathbb{E}\left[ J_t \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \log p(y_t|\mathbf{x}_t) \right] + \mathbb{E}\left[ \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} J_t \right],

where the second term accounts for direct dependence of J_t on \mathbf{w} through \log p and \log q if q also depends on \mathbf{w} (but q is separate). In practice, we ignore the direct gradient of J_t because it involves derivatives of \log q which we treat as a separate learning problem for the readout. Thus, we approximate

\nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \mathbb{E}[J_t] \approx \mathbb{E}\left[ (J_t - b_t) \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \log p(y_t|\mathbf{x}_t) \right],

where b_t is a baseline to reduce variance. Now,

\nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \log p(y_t|\mathbf{x}_t) = \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} [ y_t \log \lambda_t - \lambda_t \Delta t ] = (y_t - \lambda_t \Delta t) \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \log \lambda_t.

Since \lambda_t = \exp(\mathbf{w}^T \mathbf{x}_t), \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \log \lambda_t = \mathbf{x}_t. Hence

\nabla_{\mathbf{w}} \log p(y_t|\mathbf{x}_t) = (y_t - \lambda_t \Delta t) \mathbf{x}_t.

The term \lambda_t \Delta t is the expected spike count in the bin, which for small \Delta t is approximately the instantaneous firing rate times \Delta t. In continuous time, we interpret \lambda_t \Delta t as the conditional intensity.

Now, J_t contains terms involving y_t. The factor (J_t - b_t) acts as a modulation signal. Typically, we set b_t as an average of J_t to center it. In the context of three-factor plasticity, we identify \delta_t = J_t - b_t as the neuromodulatory signal.

Finally, we must account for the fact that synaptic changes depend on presynaptic activity over a longer time scale than a single bin. This is captured by the eligibility trace e_j(t) = \int_{-\infty}^t e^{-(t-s)/\tau_e} x_j(s) ds, which is a low-pass filtered version of the presynaptic input. The continuous-time learning rule becomes

\frac{dw_j}{dt} = \eta \, e_j(t) \, (y(t) - \lambda(t)) \, \delta(t),

where we have absorbed \Delta t and constants into \eta, and y(t) is the spike train represented as a sum of Dirac deltas. This is exactly equation (3.2). The derivation shows that the term (y(t) - \lambda(t)) arises from the score function, and \delta(t) from the modulated objective.

D.5 Including Eligibility Traces

The eligibility trace is derived from the fact that the weight update should depend on the correlation between presynaptic activity and the reward-modulated prediction error over a longer time window. In continuous time, the gradient of the log-likelihood for a spike train involves an integral over time, leading naturally to an eligibility trace. More formally, if we consider the likelihood over an interval, the gradient involves \int x(s) (y(s) - \lambda(s)) ds, which is the integral of the product of presynaptic input and prediction error. Introducing a decay in the eligibility trace corresponds to a kernel that weights recent events more strongly, which is equivalent to a moving average.

