Appendix E: Ensemble Kalman Filter Derivation

This appendix provides a derivation of the ensemble Kalman filter (EnKF) used in Chapter 6 for state and parameter estimation.

E.1 Problem Statement

We have a dynamical system

\mathbf{z}_{k+1} = \mathbf{f}_k(\mathbf{z}_k) + \mathbf{w}_k, \quad \mathbf{w}_k \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \mathbf{Q}_k),

\mathbf{y}_k = \mathbf{h}_k(\mathbf{z}_k) + \mathbf{v}_k, \quad \mathbf{v}_k \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \mathbf{R}_k),

where \mathbf{z}_k is the state (including both neural state \mathbf{x} and parameters \boldsymbol{\theta}). The functions \mathbf{f}_k and \mathbf{h}_k are nonlinear. We want to estimate the filtering distribution p(\mathbf{z}_k | \mathbf{y}_{1:k}).

E.2 Ensemble Representation

The EnKF represents the distribution by an ensemble of M samples \{\mathbf{z}_k^{(i)}\}_{i=1}^M. The algorithm proceeds in two steps: forecast and analysis.

Forecast step: Each ensemble member is propagated through the dynamics:

\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)} = \mathbf{f}_{k-1}(\mathbf{z}_{k-1}^{(i)}) + \mathbf{w}_k^{(i)},

where \mathbf{w}_k^{(i)} are independent draws from \mathcal{N}(0, \mathbf{Q}_k). This yields the forecast ensemble.

Analysis step: When a new observation \mathbf{y}_k becomes available, we update each ensemble member using a Kalman-like correction:

\mathbf{z}_k^{(i)} = \mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)} + \mathbf{K}_k \left( \mathbf{y}_k + \mathbf{v}_k^{(i)} - \mathbf{h}_k(\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)}) \right),

where \mathbf{v}_k^{(i)} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \mathbf{R}_k) are artificial perturbations to avoid underestimating uncertainty. The Kalman gain \mathbf{K}_k is computed from the ensemble covariances:

\bar{\mathbf{z}} = \frac{1}{M} \sum_{i=1}^M \mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)}, \quad
\bar{\mathbf{y}} = \frac{1}{M} \sum_{i=1}^M \mathbf{h}_k(\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)}),

\mathbf{C}_{zz} = \frac{1}{M-1} \sum_{i=1}^M (\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)} - \bar{\mathbf{z}})(\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)} - \bar{\mathbf{z}})^T,

\mathbf{C}_{yy} = \frac{1}{M-1} \sum_{i=1}^M (\mathbf{h}_k(\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)}) - \bar{\mathbf{y}})(\mathbf{h}_k(\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)}) - \bar{\mathbf{y}})^T,

\mathbf{C}_{zy} = \frac{1}{M-1} \sum_{i=1}^M (\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)} - \bar{\mathbf{z}})(\mathbf{h}_k(\mathbf{z}_{k|k-1}^{(i)}) - \bar{\mathbf{y}})^T.

Then the Kalman gain is

\mathbf{K}_k = \mathbf{C}_{zy} (\mathbf{C}_{yy} + \mathbf{R}_k)^{-1}.

E.3 Justification

For linear Gaussian systems, the EnKF with infinite ensemble size converges to the true Kalman filter. For nonlinear systems, it provides a consistent approximation under certain regularity conditions. The gain \mathbf{K}_k is the optimal linear correction given the sample covariance, analogous to the Kalman gain in the extended Kalman filter but without linearizing the model.

E.4 Convergence Theorem

Theorem E.1 (Convergence of EnKF). For a linear system with Gaussian noise, as the ensemble size M \to \infty, the EnKF estimate converges in distribution to the true Kalman filter estimate.

Proof. See [10]. For nonlinear systems, the EnKF converges to the true filtering distribution under additional assumptions of boundedness and mixing.

